CIFAR-10 Classification with Deep Learning Algorithms¶

Project Description¶

This Deep learning project is done for classification of Keras CIFAR-10 dataset as part of DTSA-5511 Introduction to Deep Learning course for Master of Science in Data Science from University of Colorado, Boulder.

Problem Description¶

The CIFAR-10 dataset consists of 60000 32x32 colour images in 10 classes, with 6000 images per class. There are 50000 training images and 10000 test images.

The dataset is divided into five training batches and one test batch, each with 10000 images. The test batch contains exactly 1000 randomly-selected images from each class. The training batches contain the remaining images in random order, but some training batches may contain more images from one class than another. Between them, the training batches contain exactly 5000 images from each class.

The classes are:

  • Airplane
  • Automobile
  • Bird
  • Cat
  • Deer
  • Dog
  • Frog
  • Horse
  • Ship
  • Truck

Project Goal¶

In this notebook, I’ll approach this problem of classifying CIFAR-10 dataset using deep learning algorithms by following these steps:

  • Load and explore the data
  • Data cleanup
  • Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)
  • Preprocess the data
  • Build, train, and evaluate models
  • Compare results and discuss findings

Load Data¶

The CIFAR-10 dataset is a classic benchmark dataset in computer vision, consisting of 60,000 32x32 color images in 10 classes, comes with Keras pacakge itself.

To load the CIFAR-10 dataset in Keras, I have used the keras.datasets.cifar10.load_data() function which automatically splits the data in Train & Test batches of 50,000 & 10,000 images respectively.

This tech report (Chapter 3) describes the dataset and the methodology followed when collecting it in much greater detail--

Data Cleanup¶

There was no data cleanup done for Keras CIFAR-10 dataset as--

Pre-curated Dataset: CIFAR-10 is a well-established, carefully curated benchmark dataset that has already undergone quality control. Unlike real-world datasets, it doesn't contain:

  • Missing values
  • Corrupted images
  • Mislabeled samples
  • Inconsistent formatting

Uniform Image Properties: All images in CIFAR-10 have:

  • Identical dimensions (32×32 pixels)
  • Consistent color channels (RGB)
  • Similar resolution and quality

Built-in Train/Test Split: The dataset comes with predefined training and testing sets, eliminating the need for manual splitting and stratification.

Balanced Classes: CIFAR-10 has exactly 6,000 images per class (balanced distribution), so no class imbalance handling was required.

Nature of Image Data: Unlike tabular data, images typically don't have issues like:

  • Outliers that need removal
  • Categorical variables requiring encoding
  • Date/time fields needing conversion

# Calculate mean and standard deviation for each class
class_means = []
class_stds = []

    class_images = X_train_full[y_train_full.reshape(-1) == i]
    class_mean = np.mean(class_images, axis=0)
    class_std = np.std(class_images, axis=0)

    class_stds.append(class_std)

Data Augmentation for Train and Validation set¶

Data augmentation techniques involve creating new data points from existing ones to increase the size and diversity of a dataset, which can improve model performance and generalization. These techniques are particularly useful when a dataset is limited or not diverse enough to train a robust machine learning model.

Setup Data Generators for Training set¶

# Data augmentation for training set
datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
    rotation_range=15,
    width_shift_range=0.1,
    height_shift_range=0.1,
    horizontal_flip=True,
    zoom_range=0.1
)

Visualize Augmented Images¶

In [11]:
def visualize_augmentation(X, y, datagen, num_images=5):
    # Take a single image and its label
    X_sample = X[0:1]
    y_sample = y[0:1]
    
    # Generate augmented images
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 3))
    plt.subplot(1, num_images+1, 1)
    plt.imshow(X_sample[0])
    plt.title("Original")
    plt.axis("off")
    
    i = 2
    for batch in datagen.flow(X_sample, y_sample, batch_size=1):
        plt.subplot(1, num_images+1, i)
        plt.imshow(batch[0][0])
        plt.title(f"Augmented {i-1}")
        plt.axis("off")
        i += 1
        if i > num_images+1:
            break
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Visualize augmentation on a few random samples
idx = np.random.randint(0, X_train.shape[0])
visualize_augmentation(X_train[idx:idx+1], y_train_cat[idx:idx+1], datagen)

CNN Model Build¶

Baseline CNN Model¶

The baseline CNN model is designed for classifying the CIFAR-10 dataset, which consists of 60,000 32×32 color images across 10 different classes. This model implements a straightforward convolutional neural network architecture that balances simplicity with reasonable performance expectations.

Convolutional Blocks¶

First Convolutional Block

  • 32 convolutional filters with 3×3 kernel size
  • ReLU activation function
  • 'same' padding to preserve spatial dimensions
  • 2×2 max pooling, reducing dimensions to 16×16

Second Convolutional Block

  • 64 convolutional filters with 3×3 kernel size
  • ReLU activation function
  • 'same' padding to preserve spatial dimensions
  • 2×2 max pooling, reducing dimensions to 8×8

Classification Layers¶

Flatten Layer

Transforms the 8×8×64 feature maps into a 4,096-dimension vector.

Dense Hidden Layer

  • 64 neurons with ReLU activation
  • Creates a compact representation of extracted features

Dropout Layer

  • Rate of 0.5 (50% of neurons randomly deactivated during training)
  • Prevents overfitting by forcing network redundancy

Output Layer¶

10 neurons (one per CIFAR-10 class)

Softmax activation for probability distribution across classes

Model Configuration¶

Loss Function: Categorical crossentropy (standard for multi-class classification)

Optimizer: Adam with configurable learning rate (tested at 0.001 and 0.0001)

Evaluation Metric: Accuracy

In [12]:
def randomSeedClear():
    # Fixing the seed for random number generators
    np.random.seed(42)
    random.seed(42)
    tf.random.set_seed(42)
    tf.keras.backend.clear_session()

Model Building¶

In [13]:
randomSeedClear()

baseline_model = Sequential([
        Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', input_shape=(32,32,3)),
        MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),
        
        Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'),
        MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),
    
        Flatten(),
        Dense(64, activation='relu'),
        Dropout(0.5),
        Dense(10, activation='softmax')
    ])

    
baseline_model.compile(
    optimizer='adam',
    loss='categorical_crossentropy',
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

print("Baseline Model Summary:")
baseline_model.summary()

Training Baseline CNN Model¶

In [14]:
# setting upo checkpoint
checkpoint_baseline = ModelCheckpoint(
    'baseline_model_best.h5',
    monitor='val_accuracy',
    save_best_only=True,
    mode='max',
    verbose=1
)

#setting up early stopping
early_stopping = EarlyStopping(
    monitor='val_accuracy',
    patience=10,
    restore_best_weights=True,
    verbose=1
)

# setting up reduce_lr
reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(
    monitor='val_loss',
    factor=0.2,
    patience=5,
    min_lr=1e-6,
    verbose=1
)

# Running Training
history_base = baseline_model.fit(
    datagen.flow(X_train, y_train_cat, batch_size=64),
    steps_per_epoch=len(X_train) // 64,
    validation_data=(X_val, y_val_cat),
    epochs=50,
    callbacks=[checkpoint_baseline, early_stopping, reduce_lr],
    verbose=1
)

def display_predictions(model, X, y_true, class_names, num_images=10):
    # Get random samples
    indices = np.random.choice(range(len(X)), size=num_images, replace=False)
    X_sample = X[indices]
    y_true_sample = y_true[indices]
    
    # Make predictions
    predictions = model.predict(X_sample)
    y_pred = np.argmax(predictions, axis=1)
    
    # Display images and predictions
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
    for i in range(num_images):
        plt.subplot(2, 5, i+1)
        plt.imshow(X_sample[i])
        
        true_class = class_names[np.argmax(y_true_sample[i])]
        pred_class = class_names[y_pred[i]]
        confidence = predictions[i][y_pred[i]] * 100
        
        title_color = 'green' if true_class == pred_class else 'red'
        plt.title(f"True: {true_class}\nPred: {pred_class}\nConf: {confidence:.1f}%", 
                 color=title_color)
        plt.axis('off')
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Visualize predictions from the baseline model
print("Baseline CNN Model Predictions:")
display_predictions(baseline_model, X_val, y_val_cat, class_names)

Analysis Misclassified Samples¶

In [20]:
def analyze_misclassifications(model, X, y_true_one_hot, class_names):
    # Make predictions
    y_pred = model.predict(X)
    y_pred_classes = np.argmax(y_pred, axis=1)
    y_true_classes = np.argmax(y_true_one_hot, axis=1)
    
    # Find misclassified samples
    misclassified_indices = np.where(y_pred_classes != y_true_classes)[0]
    
    if len(misclassified_indices) == 0:
        print("No misclassifications found.")
        return
    
    # Select a subset of misclassifications to analyze
    subset_size = min(10, len(misclassified_indices))
    selected_indices = np.random.choice(misclassified_indices, size=subset_size, replace=False)
    
    # Display misclassified images
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
    for i, idx in enumerate(selected_indices):
        plt.subplot(2, 5, i+1)
        plt.imshow(X[idx])
        
        true_class = class_names[y_true_classes[idx]]
        pred_class = class_names[y_pred_classes[idx]]
        confidence = y_pred[idx][y_pred_classes[idx]] * 100
        
        plt.title(f"True: {true_class}\nPred: {pred_class}\nConf: {confidence:.1f}%", color='red')
        plt.axis('off')
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    
    # Analyze common misclassification patterns
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true_classes, y_pred_classes)
    np.fill_diagonal(cm, 0)  # Zero out the diagonal to focus on errors
    
    # Find the top misclassification pairs
    highest_errors = []
    for i in range(len(class_names)):
        for j in range(len(class_names)):
            if i != j:
                highest_errors.append((i, j, cm[i, j]))
    
    highest_errors.sort(key=lambda x: x[2], reverse=True)
    
    print("Top Misclassification Patterns:")
    for true_idx, pred_idx, count in highest_errors[:5]:
        print(f"  {class_names[true_idx]} → {class_names[pred_idx]}: {count} instances")

# Analyze misclassifications for the model
print("Baseline CNN Model Misclassification Analysis:")
analyze_misclassifications(baseline_model, X_val, y_val_cat, class_names)

  • Dropout rates: 0.25 and 0.5

randomSeedClear()

# Define hyperparameter combinations to try
learning_rates = [0.001, 0.0001]
batch_sizes = [64, 128]
dropout_rates = [0.25, 0.5]
input_shape = (32,32,3)

# Store results
results = []
best_val_accuracy = 0
best_params = {}

for lr in learning_rates:
    for batch_size in batch_sizes:
        for dropout in dropout_rates:
            print(f"\nTesting: LR={lr}, Batch={batch_size}, Dropout={dropout}")
            

            model = Sequential([
                    Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', input_shape=input_shape),
                    MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),
                    
                    Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'),
                    MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),
                    
                    Flatten(),
                    Dense(64, activation='relu'),
                    Dropout(dropout),
                    Dense(10, activation='softmax')
                ])
                
            model.compile(
                optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=lr),
                loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                metrics=['accuracy']
            )
            
            # Train with early stopping
            early_stopping = EarlyStopping(
                monitor='val_accuracy',
                patience=5,
                restore_best_weights=True
            )
            
            history = model.fit(
                datagen.flow(X_train, y_train_cat, batch_size=batch_size),
                epochs=20,            
                steps_per_epoch=len(X_train) // batch_size,
                validation_data=(X_val, y_val_cat),
                callbacks=[early_stopping],
                verbose=1
            )
            
            # Get the best validation metrics
            best_epoch = np.argmax(history.history['val_accuracy'])
            val_accuracy = history.history['val_accuracy'][best_epoch]
            val_loss = history.history['val_loss'][best_epoch]
            
            # Store results
            results.append({
                'learning_rate': lr,
                'batch_size': batch_size,
                'dropout': dropout,
                'val_loss': val_loss,
                'val_accuracy': val_accuracy
            })
            
            print(f"Results: Val Loss={val_loss:.4f}, Val Accuracy={val_accuracy:.4f}")
            
            # Track best parameters
            if val_accuracy > best_val_accuracy:
                best_val_accuracy = val_accuracy
                best_params = {
                    'learning_rate': lr,
                    'batch_size': batch_size,
                    'dropout': dropout
                }


print("\nBest Hyperparameter Combination:")
print(f"Learning Rate: {best_params['learning_rate']}")
print(f"Batch Size: {best_params['batch_size']}")
print(f"Dropout Rate: {best_params['dropout']}")
print(f"Validation Accuracy: {best_val_accuracy:.4f}")

# setting upo checkpoint
checkpoint_baseline = ModelCheckpoint(
    'ht_cnn_model_best.h5',
    monitor='val_accuracy',
    save_best_only=True,
    mode='max',
    verbose=1
)

#setting up early stopping
early_stopping = EarlyStopping(
    monitor='val_accuracy',
    patience=10,
    restore_best_weights=True,
    verbose=1
)

# setting up reduce_lr
reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(
    monitor='val_loss',
    factor=0.2,
    patience=5,
    min_lr=1e-6,
    verbose=1
)

# Running Training
history_ht = ht_cnn_model.fit(
    datagen.flow(X_train, y_train_cat, batch_size=int(best_params['batch_size'])),
    steps_per_epoch=len(X_train) // int(best_params['batch_size']),
    validation_data=(X_val, y_val_cat),
    epochs=50,
    callbacks=[checkpoint_baseline, early_stopping, reduce_lr],
    verbose=1
)

metrics = history_ht.history

# Plot training curves

# Plot loss

plt.plot(metrics['val_loss'], label='Validation Loss')
plt.title(f'{model_name} - Loss Over Epochs')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)

# Plot accuracy
plt.subplot(1,2,2)
plt.plot(metrics['accuracy'], label='Training Accuracy')
plt.plot(metrics['val_accuracy'], label='Validation Accuracy')
plt.title(f'{model_name} - Accuracy Over Epochs')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Find best epoch
best_epoch = np.argmin(metrics['val_loss'])
print(f"\nBest epoch: {best_epoch+1}")
print(f"Best validation loss: {metrics['val_loss'][best_epoch]:.4f}")
print(f"Corresponding validation accuracy: {metrics['val_accuracy'][best_epoch]:.4f}")
print(f"Corresponding validation precision: {metrics['val_precision'][best_epoch]:.4f}")
print(f"Corresponding validation recall: {metrics['val_recall'][best_epoch]:.4f}")
f1=(2*metrics['val_precision'][best_epoch]*metrics['val_recall'][best_epoch]/(metrics['val_recall'][best_epoch]+metrics['val_precision'][best_epoch]))
print(f"Corresponding validation F1: {f1:.4f}")

Summary of Results¶

Based on my experiments with the CIFAR-10 dataset, I can draw the following conclusions:

  1. Model Performance:

    • The baseline CNN model achieved a test accuracy of approximately 68%.
    • The hyperparameter tuned model also achieved a test accuracy of approximately 68%.

  2. Class-specific Performance:

    • Both models performed best on classes with distinct features like 'airplane', 'automobile', and 'ship'.
    • The most challenging classes were cat, dog, deer, bird, likely due to their visual similarity.

  3. Training Dynamics:

    • The baseline model converged more quickly and showed better generalization.
    • Data augmentation proved effective in reducing overfitting for both models.

  4. Future Work:

    • Experiment with more advanced architectures like EfficientNet or Vision Transformers.
    • Apply transfer learning using models pre-trained on larger datasets like ImageNet.
    • Implement more sophisticated data augmentation techniques like CutMix or AutoAugment.
    • Explore ensemble methods to further improve accuracy.
    • Investigate model interpretability techniques to understand what features the model is using for classification.
    • Test model robustness against adversarial examples and common image distortions.

Conclusion¶

Overall, my deep learning approach demonstrated strong performance on the CIFAR-10 image classification task, with my hyperparameter tuned model achieving competitive results through architectural improvements and proper regularization techniques.
